@PrinceJvstin There was a section that passed a 19th mine that was an abandoned claim & sometime between seasons some jerk went & tried to dig into the hillside & collapsed our trail. He might still be in there, who knows?

@PrinceJvstin Definitely the prepared. There are a lot of people out there who know, but you don't fuck around. Lots of hunters & old mines that collapse on a whim. The archaeological site I worked on was a 3 mile hike in to 6000 ft.

@PrinceJvstin There are some melt meadows in the Catherine Creek area that I feel are literal slices of heaven. I grew up just going into the woods every chance I got. We all did out there. My first work as an archaeologist was a Chinese mining camp out there. The history there is...wild.

@PrinceJvstin Whole area is just full of hot springs & weird geological formations. It is absolutely gorgeous. Hard to get to/travel in the winter because whole area is just mountain range after mountain range. I've got horror stories. 100 car pileup just last month. https://t.co/2hmClcvvXz

@PrinceJvstin Joseph is an interesting town, too. Named after Chief Joseph of the Nez Perce as this was his people's territory. Now a bronze statuary artist's haven. Hot Lake Hotel near Union is FASCINATING (everyone has a ghost story about it...everyone). Union Hotel is GORGEOUS, too.

@PrinceJvstin My high school geology club hiked to the lake. The water is AMAZING. Easier to access is Wallowa Lake where there are Roosevelt Elk who will knock you over to steal your ice cream (two times, thanks elk) & take a tram to the top & see the whole glacial landscape.

@PrinceJvstin I grew up there. The NE part is totally different from everywhere else (except the Klamath area, though different ages) because it is an accreted terrain (scraped off ocean plate & island volcanoes  from tectonic action in the Paleozoic & Mesozoic) FOSSILS EVERYWHERE.
